{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17477393","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17477393"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:01:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:01:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14512"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14512","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14512"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.19,0.01,0.74,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7207"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104831"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7207"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14512"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87217"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"96"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1569"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2705"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"12916"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17475"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38015"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104831"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with a 24-hour history of vomiting. She has a history of type 1 diabetes with poor glycaemic control and has spent the last three days at a friend\u0027s house. She appears acutely unwell.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she is tachypnoeic and tachycardic with a blood pressure of 85/60 mmHg. Her peripheries are cool and her lips are dry. She responds to voice and pain but is very lethargic. Venous blood gas analysis after intravenous cannulation reveals:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpH 6.85 (7.35-7.45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EpCO2 25 mmHg (35-45)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBicarbonate 3 mmol/L (22-26)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBase excess -28 mmol/L (-2 to +2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESodium 132 mmol/L (135-145)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPotassium 5.7 mmol/L (3.5-5.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucose 40 mmol/L (3.9-7.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intravenous bicarbonate infusion","Intravenous insulin infusion","Intravenous mannitol","Intravenous normal saline bolus","Subcutaneous insulin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA), a medical emergency characterised by hyperglycaemia, metabolic acidosis, and ketonemia. The most appropriate initial management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous normal saline bolus\u003C/strong\u003E. Fluid resuscitation is crucial in DKA to correct hypovolemia, improve tissue perfusion, and reduce glucose levels through dilution and improved renal perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous insulin infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is an essential component of DKA management, but it should not be the initial step. Insulin therapy is typically started after the first hour of fluid resuscitation to avoid rapid shifts in osmolality and potential complications like cerebral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous bicarbonate infusion\u003C/strong\u003E is generally not recommended in DKA, even with severe acidosis. The acidosis typically resolves with proper fluid and insulin therapy. Bicarbonate therapy can potentially cause paradoxical CNS acidosis and hypokalaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous mannitol\u003C/strong\u003E is used in the treatment of cerebral oedema, a rare but serious complication of DKA. However, it is not part of the initial management unless there are specific signs of cerebral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESubcutaneous insulin\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in the acute management of DKA. The absorption of subcutaneous insulin can be unpredictable in the setting of dehydration and poor peripheral perfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initial fluid resuscitation, the next steps in management would include starting an insulin infusion, correcting electrolyte imbalances (particularly potassium), and addressing any underlying precipitating factors. Close monitoring of clinical status, fluid balance, and biochemical parameters is crucial throughout the treatment of DKA.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) is a medical emergency characterised by hyperglycaemia, metabolic acidosis, and ketonemia.","Initial management of diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) focuses on fluid resuscitation with normal saline to correct hypovolemia.","Insulin therapy should not be initiated until after initial fluid resuscitation in diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) management."],"references":["Gosmanov AR, Gosmanova EO, Kitabchi AE. Hyperglycemic Crises: Diabetic Ketoacidosis and Hyperglycemic Hyperosmolar State. [Updated 2021 May 9]. In: Feingold KR, Anawalt B, Blackman MR, et al., editors. Endotext [Internet]. South Dartmouth (MA): MDText.com, Inc.; 2000-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK279052/","Gripp KE, Trottier ED, Thakore S, Sniderman J, Lawrence S. Current recommendations for management of paediatric diabetic ketoacidosis. Paediatrics \u0026 Child Health. 2023;28(2):128-32. Available at: https://academic.oup.com/pch/article/28/2/128/7151114"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87217"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14512"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"87217","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/87217"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-05T09:45:40+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-05T09:45:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7207"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104831"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","